WEBVTT

00:00:00.320 --> 00:00:06.720
All right, so this is a talk about something that I've been thinking about the last couple of years

00:00:07.360 --> 00:00:13.840
and it started with two years of nothing working, as in a trashed a couple of parcels

00:00:13.840 --> 00:00:19.680
and it just didn't work. And then last Christmas while I was returning for very slight surgery

00:00:20.240 --> 00:00:23.520
I had an idea and this is what this talk is about.

00:00:23.520 --> 00:00:33.919
So we're in the modeling workflow and we're done. We found the right model we want and we're happy with it

00:00:34.720 --> 00:00:39.279
and then the next question is what should we do now? And there's a lot of different things to do

00:00:39.279 --> 00:00:45.840
with it, depends on what we want to do. It could be inference, it could be other types of extractions

00:00:46.959 --> 00:00:52.000
but what I'm really focused on right here is making predictions from this model we decided

00:00:52.000 --> 00:01:00.880
it was the best model ever. To be able to do this I have pulled out today this little model

00:01:00.880 --> 00:01:07.440
using the Penguins dataset we all know and love. I have a fairly simple recipe that deals with

00:01:07.440 --> 00:01:12.480
missing values, we create dummy variables, we remove some variables that doesn't seem like

00:01:12.480 --> 00:01:19.440
they are useful, centering and scaling at the end. Then we're using the bonsai package to provide

00:01:19.440 --> 00:01:26.000
the party head engine for a decision tree. We combine it all in a workflow and fit it.

00:01:27.440 --> 00:01:34.400
This is not a great model but it's very useful to showcase everything I need for this talk.

00:01:36.080 --> 00:01:41.440
And we can use it to predict like we normally would. It follows the tidy models prediction

00:01:41.440 --> 00:01:49.919
guarantee, it's always a table and it always has the right number of rows, right name and everything.

00:01:52.400 --> 00:01:57.760
To sidestep a little bit I want to talk about one of my favorite packages that I didn't write myself.

00:01:58.559 --> 00:02:05.199
It's called tidy predict and what it does it is that it allows us to take a fitted model

00:02:06.160 --> 00:02:09.440
and allows us to run predictions inside a database.

00:02:10.399 --> 00:02:15.759
And the way it does that is that it parses the model and strats all the sufficient information

00:02:16.720 --> 00:02:25.039
and then reconstructs our formula that can then be evaluated in SQL or something else because

00:02:25.039 --> 00:02:32.399
of the great work done stuff like DT plier, DB plier, DBI and all of that that allows us to

00:02:32.479 --> 00:02:37.520
translate our code into code that needs to be run other places.

00:02:39.360 --> 00:02:44.399
And tidy predict works with a lot of different types of models. We have linear models, we have

00:02:44.399 --> 00:02:51.199
forest models, other types of tree models, all different types of models. But it has a limitation

00:02:52.160 --> 00:02:56.080
and the limitation is that we're only allowed one equation.

00:02:56.240 --> 00:03:02.399
And this means that it ends up not being that useful for a lot of people because if you have

00:03:02.399 --> 00:03:10.080
a recipe it doesn't work because that's why it crashed for me because if you try to recursively

00:03:10.080 --> 00:03:19.119
reconstruct a recipe and a model up here together you did a for even a modest data set you get

00:03:19.279 --> 00:03:25.520
50,000 terabytes of SQL strings and it doesn't like that.

00:03:28.960 --> 00:03:33.360
For the same reason we end up with a lot of redundant information that needs to

00:03:34.240 --> 00:03:37.440
be calculated over and over again. If you're working with a tree model

00:03:38.080 --> 00:03:43.119
calculating when to split has to happen multiple times and it's inefficient.

00:03:44.000 --> 00:03:51.520
And lastly same reason we have one equation we can't get easy classification probabilities

00:03:51.520 --> 00:03:56.800
because we can only get one vector out at the end. So we can't get a vector for each class.

00:03:57.440 --> 00:04:02.080
So we can get it technically for the two class but then we're limited.

00:04:04.080 --> 00:04:10.960
And this is where my contribution to this whole problem is where I added the orbital package.

00:04:13.839 --> 00:04:23.279
So what so stepping back one more time is we think about how any given model works.

00:04:24.079 --> 00:04:28.160
And a lot of times especially when we're like just practitioners and we think we don't really

00:04:29.200 --> 00:04:34.559
we need to have predictions done we think about these models as more of a black box of data

00:04:34.559 --> 00:04:40.959
coming in predictions coming out. But sometimes we can peel back for some of these types of models

00:04:41.040 --> 00:04:47.440
especially a tree-based model that I used. And we can see that it follows this tree-based

00:04:47.440 --> 00:04:54.000
structure where at first we see is the build length less or greater like less or equal to

00:04:54.000 --> 00:04:58.640
some value. If that's true then we find some other thing and then at the end we have a

00:04:58.640 --> 00:05:04.320
that's the prediction right there. Here is just a normal print that comes out

00:05:04.880 --> 00:05:12.160
but we could rewrite it as a series of if-else statements that then is equivalent to prediction.

00:05:13.519 --> 00:05:18.720
And lastly we could also turn into a one-liner from taste using the taste when function

00:05:18.720 --> 00:05:23.119
from dplyr which is essentially what tidy predict is doing.

00:05:25.920 --> 00:05:32.320
But we are not just working with the single model we're also working with a workflow

00:05:32.320 --> 00:05:39.200
which includes everything that happens before. Because you might have noticed that this tree

00:05:40.399 --> 00:05:46.559
used let a build length total point does negative because it has been normalized

00:05:47.279 --> 00:05:52.079
earlier in this recipe so we need to make sure that when we do the predictions it needs the

00:05:52.079 --> 00:05:59.920
right data at the right time. So we can think of this recipe as it works sequentially it comes in

00:06:00.880 --> 00:06:08.160
it handles all the nominal predictors using step up known then all the numeric predictors

00:06:08.160 --> 00:06:15.679
with imputed median and so on and so forth. But we can rethink this as a series of statements

00:06:15.679 --> 00:06:23.119
much like in a mutate call. So at the beginning we have some statements that

00:06:23.200 --> 00:06:31.279
looks to see if the values are na and then puts in unknown. Likewise when we do the impute

00:06:31.279 --> 00:06:38.399
median it's the same idea we find out if the values are na or not and pulls them in and we

00:06:38.399 --> 00:06:45.519
move on. And then step dummy you know the drill by now we can think of each recipe step as doing

00:06:45.519 --> 00:06:52.320
some calculations one after another in a sequential way ending up with our predictions at the end.

00:06:54.079 --> 00:07:03.279
But if we notice in our statement at the end not all the variables from earlier were used.

00:07:03.279 --> 00:07:09.279
The ones we have left is set mail, build length and species chinstrap.

00:07:10.239 --> 00:07:14.880
So now let's go in reverse. So now we go back up and look at when we

00:07:14.880 --> 00:07:20.880
when we when we send out all the variables and we notice that only three out of the eight

00:07:20.880 --> 00:07:25.279
variables at that point in time were used. So we can just gray out the rest.

00:07:26.239 --> 00:07:31.040
We continue doing this going up now what we're centering, staling,

00:07:33.839 --> 00:07:39.519
identifying the ones that needs to happen for later use and so on and so forth. So now we

00:07:39.679 --> 00:07:46.000
and so on and so forth. So now we identified all the calculations that need to happen

00:07:46.000 --> 00:07:50.399
to be able to provide prediction and we just throw away everything that doesn't.

00:07:51.600 --> 00:07:59.200
So in essence if we can do this math we are able to provide the equivalent of a prediction.

00:08:01.200 --> 00:08:06.959
And that's in essence what the orbital package will do. So you load up all the orbital and run

00:08:06.959 --> 00:08:13.519
the orbital function on our fitted workflow and it creates an object that has all the sufficient

00:08:13.519 --> 00:08:21.119
information to do predictions that are equivalent to the original predict method.

00:08:22.559 --> 00:08:30.799
Before I move on I want to make it clear that this object by itself is quite small and it doesn't

00:08:30.799 --> 00:08:37.599
require any of the previous packages to work. So if you save this file to a disk and load it up in

00:08:37.599 --> 00:08:41.840
a new session you don't need tidy models, you don't need parsing, you don't need bonsai, you don't need

00:08:41.840 --> 00:08:48.719
nothing. You just need orbital. So that's already a quite a bit deep trees in dependencies right here.

00:08:50.080 --> 00:08:55.760
So now we have the object we have two main things we can do prediction and code generation and I

00:08:55.760 --> 00:09:01.760
want to start prediction. And we predict just like we did before. So with the orbital object

00:09:01.760 --> 00:09:07.440
we can use the predict function on it and we see that the predictions are identical to the

00:09:07.440 --> 00:09:16.320
predictions that happened through the tidy models object down to some rounding like the 12 15th

00:09:16.320 --> 00:09:24.000
decimal place. But I want to take this a step further so then we know that it works with a

00:09:24.000 --> 00:09:29.280
plain table. We can predict with it and get it back. But where it becomes interesting is if we

00:09:29.280 --> 00:09:35.119
set up a little bit of infrastructure. Here I spin up a ephemeral

00:09:37.599 --> 00:09:45.039
c12 lite server and I put the penguins data in this server. I'm able to predict directly in the

00:09:45.039 --> 00:09:53.599
database. So these predictions are evaluated c12 that happens not inside R in a database somewhere.

00:09:54.000 --> 00:09:58.719
So if you can give me a connection up yet and some data that matches the data that this model

00:09:58.719 --> 00:10:04.159
is fitted on we can predict in it. And because we can do this we can also do something like in a

00:10:04.159 --> 00:10:12.719
spot database directly in using everything that spot has to offer not inside R. Also works with

00:10:12.719 --> 00:10:20.320
things like arrow. The print is nice but I promise that it returns the same thing and it will also

00:10:20.320 --> 00:10:28.640
work with niceties like .db. So we have like on test prediction but not inside the R session.

00:10:33.440 --> 00:10:39.280
So basically if you can give me some data in a way we can predict on it. But there's another

00:10:39.280 --> 00:10:46.719
side to the story which is a little bit how all of this works and that is the notion of code

00:10:46.719 --> 00:10:55.840
generation. So I showed you how we can do predictions in a c12 database. But we can also

00:10:55.840 --> 00:11:04.640
just not use R anymore. We take our orbital object and we bring back our c12 connection. Here we're

00:11:04.640 --> 00:11:14.320
using c12 lite connection and we use them together and it exports out the c12 that when run in this

00:11:14.320 --> 00:11:23.280
database does the same thing as prediction. It's important to note that we need the right c12.

00:11:23.919 --> 00:11:28.239
It needs to be the right connection for where you're using it because all the different c12

00:11:28.239 --> 00:11:33.760
databases have slightly different flavors and different names for things. But this should work

00:11:33.840 --> 00:11:44.640
on any known database that has support from the dpi packages. This is also the way that .db works

00:11:44.640 --> 00:11:54.799
because the developers behind .db have enabled these translations. Let's try another fun thing.

00:11:55.599 --> 00:11:59.840
So we're going back into R but we want to do predictions but we actually don't even want to

00:11:59.840 --> 00:12:05.200
use orbital. We just want to spin up a shiny app and we want to have it lean and mean so it like

00:12:05.200 --> 00:12:12.400
runs fast and everything you need. So to do that first we need a function that does the prediction.

00:12:13.280 --> 00:12:19.200
So we have a function here called orbital rfun. You give it the orbital object and a file name

00:12:19.919 --> 00:12:26.960
and what it will do is it will write to a file a function definition that when applied to a data

00:12:26.960 --> 00:12:34.080
set produces predictions that are equivalent to the predictions we saw before. So with that in mind

00:12:34.080 --> 00:12:40.960
and so this one needs dplyr because some of the steps needed dplyr to work but it doesn't need

00:12:40.960 --> 00:12:49.359
orbital it just needs dplyr to work. So with that in mind we can spin up a simple ui that matches

00:12:50.320 --> 00:12:52.799
the input that we are expecting.

00:12:54.880 --> 00:13:01.760
And the server side we're taking all the input putting it in a data frame putting it into this

00:13:01.760 --> 00:13:09.280
function that we sourced in and now I'm just rendering it to text on a shiny app. So now we

00:13:09.280 --> 00:13:18.799
have a slightly modified shiny app so it looks nice but in essence not using tidy models not

00:13:18.799 --> 00:13:27.520
using orbital at least in that shiny app we have live predictions that does exactly what you expect.

00:13:32.960 --> 00:13:40.000
And we can take it one step further. So the same way I showed how we can generate

00:13:41.359 --> 00:13:47.599
an rfunction you can use the same technique. So this isn't implemented but I spent around 10

00:13:47.599 --> 00:13:56.880
minutes with my very rudimentary javascript knowledge and I translated the r function

00:13:56.880 --> 00:14:02.719
that was outputted earlier into a javascript function and now we have

00:14:04.799 --> 00:14:10.799
tidy models prediction using pure javascript in a website. So then we just like we can slide

00:14:10.799 --> 00:14:18.080
things around and it does the predictions the same way we expect them to in the browser we're

00:14:18.080 --> 00:14:24.640
not using r we're not using anything else. And this is just a simple javascript example to show

00:14:24.640 --> 00:14:30.960
what can really be done. You could also you could technically also translate it to a python function

00:14:30.960 --> 00:14:38.479
so we can do python predictions of like from tidy models but you can also do java you can do c

00:14:38.479 --> 00:14:45.440
whatever you have the domain knowledge to do that is the right place for you to deploy this prediction model.

00:14:47.119 --> 00:14:51.679
All right so I said a lot of nice things about the package but there's some downsides.

00:14:52.799 --> 00:14:59.760
The main downside of why you don't want to use this package is that not all models are supported.

00:15:01.039 --> 00:15:05.840
And there's two reasons why not supported one of them is that people we haven't done it yet

00:15:06.559 --> 00:15:14.239
and the other reason is that it is feasibly impossible to do. So that is models that like

00:15:14.239 --> 00:15:18.719
distance-based models like nearest neighbor models you can't rewrite them as a series of

00:15:18.719 --> 00:15:24.239
expressions it's going to be too long. But other types of tree or linear based models

00:15:24.239 --> 00:15:28.799
could be implemented so you want them find an issue and it can happen.

00:15:29.679 --> 00:15:36.159
Another major downside which is the upside of using tidy models is that there's no input chatting.

00:15:36.799 --> 00:15:44.159
So it assumes that all the data coming into these functions are exactly as before. So if you have a

00:15:44.159 --> 00:15:51.440
new label in your factor it doesn't know what to deal with it and it might work but it might trash.

00:15:52.320 --> 00:15:57.359
If something was expected to be a numeric but comes out as a date time variable

00:15:58.320 --> 00:15:59.919
it also probably will trash.

00:16:02.080 --> 00:16:06.239
But you're also gaining a little like a slight speed in that way because we're not spending time

00:16:06.239 --> 00:16:13.359
actually chatting. And the last time which is will go away over time is that this is very new.

00:16:13.359 --> 00:16:20.880
It was pushed to train about 15 days ago and this is the first time I've told people outside my team

00:16:20.880 --> 00:16:28.080
about it. But it can do a lot of neat things and this is where we come back to the pros that

00:16:29.119 --> 00:16:35.760
we don't have to spin up a data container with all of tidy models and all the extra dependencies we

00:16:35.760 --> 00:16:45.599
need. We can either use orbital or work like straight in databases or like stepping R entirely.

00:16:46.559 --> 00:16:54.239
And I see a lot of potential in this package and this is where I'm going to lead off. This will

00:16:54.239 --> 00:17:01.200
send you to the documentation of the package where I'm outlining a little bit more what it can and

00:17:01.200 --> 00:17:01.679
can't do.

00:17:12.160 --> 00:17:14.319
Thank you Emil. That was great. I look forward to using it.

